const BPN_DATA = [
  { name:"Afghanistan", region:"Asia", fatfBlack:false, fatfGrey:false, cryptoBan:true, comp:false, bodies:["OFAC","EU","UK"], status:P, notes:"PROHIBITED — Crypto ban + targeted sanctions + failed state infrastructure.\n\nThe Taliban government reinstated a blanket prohibition on all cryptocurrency activity via decree in 2022, making any financial engagement with Afghanistan's digital asset ecosystem unlawful. Separately, OFAC maintains targeted designations on Taliban leadership and affiliated entities; the EU and UK have parallel designation regimes covering senior Taliban officials and associated networks.\n\nBeyond the crypto ban and sanctions exposure, Afghanistan presents a complete KYC/KYB impossibility: there is no functioning civil registry, no AML/CFT supervisory authority, no effective financial intelligence unit, and no credible law enforcement capacity. Any payment flows involving Afghan counterparties carry material risk of benefiting sanctioned individuals or financing terrorism, drug trafficking (Afghanistan produces over 80% of global illicit opium), or arms procurement. Business prohibited on all grounds." },
  { name:"Algeria", region:"Africa", fatfBlack:false, fatfGrey:true, cryptoBan:true, comp:false, bodies:[], status:P, notes:"PROHIBITED — Crypto ban + FATF grey list.\n\nAlgeria enacted a comprehensive ban on the purchase, sale, use, and possession of virtual currencies under Finance Law 18-04 (Article 117bis), effective 2018. The prohibition applies to all natural and legal persons and carries criminal penalties. Algeria was added to the FATF grey list in October 2024, reflecting strategic deficiencies in its AML/CFT framework — particularly around beneficial ownership transparency, financial intelligence unit effectiveness, and cross-border cash controls.\n\nThe combination of an active crypto ban — which makes any BPN transaction directly unlawful under Algerian law — and the FATF grey listing makes Algeria prohibited for all BPN business." },
  { name:"Angola", region:"Africa", fatfBlack:false, fatfGrey:true, cryptoBan:false, comp:false, bodies:[], status:E, notes:"HIGH RISK — FATF grey list + state capture risk.\n\nAngola was added to the FATF grey list in October 2024. FATF identified deficiencies in AML/CFT supervision of financial institutions, weak beneficial ownership frameworks, and insufficient investigation and prosecution of complex money laundering cases.\n\nAngola's economy is heavily oil-dependent, which historically created systemic state capture risk. The kleptocratic networks developed under the Dos Santos era facilitated large-scale international asset laundering through opaque corporate structures — Isabel dos Santos's documented network (Panama Papers, Luanda Leaks) illustrates the sophistication of Angolan state-linked capital flight. While the Lourenço government has pursued some anti-corruption reforms, the structural vulnerabilities remain significant.\n\nBPN onboarding in Angola requires enhanced due diligence including full beneficial ownership chain verification, source of funds documentation for any oil or government-adjacent business, and rigorous screening against OFAC/EU designation lists for politically exposed persons." },
  { name:"Bangladesh", region:"Asia", fatfBlack:false, fatfGrey:false, cryptoBan:true, comp:false, bodies:[], status:P, notes:"PROHIBITED — Crypto ban.\n\nBangladesh Bank issued a circular in 2017 prohibiting all financial institutions from facilitating cryptocurrency transactions, reinforced under the Digital Security Act. The ban makes any BPN-facilitated payment flow involving Bangladeshi counterparties, financial institutions, or currency conversions unlawful under Bangladeshi law. Bangladesh Bank has prosecuted individuals for crypto-related transactions and the legal posture has not liberalised as of March 2026. Business prohibited due to crypto ban." },
  { name:"Belarus", region:"Europe", fatfBlack:false, fatfGrey:false, cryptoBan:false, comp:false, bodies:["OFAC","EU","UK"], status:P, notes:"PROHIBITED — Comprehensive targeted sanctions.\n\nFollowing the fraudulent August 2020 presidential election and the violent suppression of pro-democracy protests, the United States, European Union, and United Kingdom imposed successive rounds of targeted sanctions on the Lukashenko regime, senior security officials, and key economic enablers. Sanctions were intensified after the forced diversion of Ryanair flight FR4978 in May 2021 and Belarus's active facilitation of Russia's invasion of Ukraine, including use of Belarusian territory for the initial attack and ongoing logistical support.\n\nSanctioned sectors include potash, petroleum products, financial services, and defence. The Central Bank of Belarus and several major state-owned banks are designated. Given the depth of sanctions coverage, the elevated risk of financial relationships benefiting designated parties through intermediary structures, and the authoritarian governance context eliminating any meaningful rule of law, business is prohibited across all BPN entities." },
  { name:"Bolivia", region:"Americas", fatfBlack:false, fatfGrey:true, cryptoBan:true, comp:false, bodies:[], status:P, notes:"PROHIBITED — Crypto ban + FATF grey list.\n\nThe Central Bank of Bolivia enacted a comprehensive ban on cryptocurrency under Circular 001-2014, prohibiting all financial institutions and their customers from transacting in any currency not issued or authorised by the state. Bolivia was added to the FATF grey list in June 2025 following a mutual evaluation that found significant weaknesses in its AML/CFT framework, including limited effectiveness of financial intelligence analysis and inadequate supervision of non-financial businesses and professions.\n\nBoth the active crypto ban and the FATF grey listing independently trigger a prohibited classification under BPN policy." },
  { name:"Bulgaria", region:"Europe", fatfBlack:false, fatfGrey:true, cryptoBan:false, comp:false, bodies:[], status:E, notes:"HIGH RISK — FATF grey list.\n\nBulgaria, an EU member state, was added to the FATF grey list following a mutual evaluation identifying systemic failures in its AML/CFT regime. Key deficiencies included weak beneficial ownership registration and verification, ineffective investigation and prosecution of money laundering, inadequate confiscation of criminal proceeds, and insufficient oversight of high-risk sectors including real estate, lawyers, and company service providers.\n\nBulgaria has historically been documented as a hub for organised crime money laundering — particularly by Eastern European criminal networks — with real estate, gambling, and trade-based laundering as primary mechanisms. The FATF grey listing reflects strategic-level deficiencies, not technical shortcomings.\n\nEnhanced due diligence is required for all BPN corporate onboarding, including rigorous beneficial ownership verification and PEP screening given Bulgaria's history of state-linked corruption." },
  { name:"Cameroon", region:"Africa", fatfBlack:false, fatfGrey:true, cryptoBan:false, comp:false, bodies:[], status:E, notes:"HIGH RISK — FATF grey list + armed conflict terrorism financing risk.\n\nCameroon was placed on the FATF grey list following identification of deficiencies including weak financial intelligence, inadequate supervision of the non-profit sector, and insufficient investigation of complex ML/TF cases.\n\nThe country faces a protracted armed conflict in its anglophone northwest and southwest regions (the 'Ambazonia' separatist conflict), ongoing since 2016. This creates a localised terrorism financing risk: armed groups require funding for weapons and logistics, and informal cross-border payment flows in conflict zones are extremely difficult to monitor. Cameroon also borders the CAR and the Lake Chad Basin, which are active terrorist theatres (Boko Haram, ISWAP). Enhanced due diligence is required, including geographic risk mapping of counterparty locations and screening against FATF/UN designated entity lists." },
  { name:"Central African Republic", region:"Africa", fatfBlack:false, fatfGrey:false, cryptoBan:false, comp:false, bodies:["OFAC","EU","UN","UK"], status:P, notes:"PROHIBITED — UN arms embargo + comprehensive multi-body sanctions + failed state.\n\nThe UN Security Council imposed a comprehensive arms embargo on the CAR in 2013 (extended annually) and a targeted sanctions regime (SC Resolution 2399) designating individuals obstructing the peace process, committing human rights violations, or supporting armed groups. OFAC, the EU, and the UK each maintain parallel designation lists including armed group leaders, mercenaries (including Wagner/Africa Corps-affiliated individuals), and government officials.\n\nThe CAR has no functioning AML/CFT framework, no credible supervisory authority, and no effective civil registry. Russian mercenary networks (previously Wagner Group, now Africa Corps) exercise de facto influence over security and economic sectors including gold and diamond mining. Any financial flows into the CAR carry an extreme risk of benefiting sanctioned armed groups or financing atrocity crimes. Business absolutely prohibited." },
  { name:"China", region:"Asia", fatfBlack:false, fatfGrey:false, cryptoBan:true, comp:false, bodies:[], status:P, notes:"PROHIBITED — Comprehensive crypto ban with explicit extraterritorial application.\n\nThe People's Bank of China, together with nine other regulatory bodies, issued a joint notice in September 2021 declaring all cryptocurrency-related business activities illegal. This includes not only trading and exchange but explicitly extends to 'providing services to domestic residents' by overseas exchanges or infrastructure providers — meaning the prohibition is not limited to entities operating within China.\n\nBPN, as a regulated financial services participant with payment infrastructure, cannot operate in a jurisdiction with an absolute legal ban carrying criminal penalties. Note: Hong Kong operates under a separate legal framework and has established a dedicated VASP licensing regime under the AMLO — it is listed independently as Allowed. Mainland China business is prohibited." },
  { name:"Cote d'Ivoire", region:"Africa", fatfBlack:false, fatfGrey:true, cryptoBan:false, comp:false, bodies:[], status:E, notes:"HIGH RISK — FATF grey list + West Africa regional risk.\n\nCôte d'Ivoire was added to the FATF grey list in October 2024. FATF identified deficiencies including inadequate beneficial ownership frameworks, weak supervision of designated non-financial businesses and professions, insufficient financial intelligence analysis, and limited effectiveness of the AML/CFT framework in the real estate and informal sectors.\n\nAs the largest economy in francophone West Africa and home to Abidjan — the region's primary financial centre — Côte d'Ivoire is also exposed to ML/TF spillover from neighbouring Mali and Burkina Faso, where jihadist groups (JNIM, ISGS) have significant territorial presence and are expanding southward. Cross-border commodity trade (cocoa, cashew, gold) presents trade-based money laundering risk. Enhanced due diligence required." },
  { name:"Cuba", region:"Americas", fatfBlack:false, fatfGrey:false, cryptoBan:false, comp:true, bodies:["OFAC"], status:P, notes:"PROHIBITED — Comprehensive US sanctions (CACR).\n\nCuba has been subject to comprehensive US economic sanctions under the Cuban Assets Control Regulations (31 CFR Part 515) since 1963. The CACR prohibits virtually all financial transactions involving Cuba or Cuban nationals by US persons and entities, including the processing of payments, providing financial services, or engaging in trade.\n\nFor BPN, as a US-nexus entity (Polygon Labs is US-incorporated), any Cuban counterparty transaction would constitute a strict liability OFAC violation with no general licence available for the contemplated activities. Business is absolutely prohibited." },
  { name:"DR Congo", region:"Africa", fatfBlack:false, fatfGrey:true, cryptoBan:false, comp:false, bodies:["OFAC","EU","UN","UK"], status:P, notes:"PROHIBITED — UN arms embargo + targeted multi-body sanctions + active armed conflict + conflict minerals exposure.\n\nThe UN Security Council imposed a comprehensive arms embargo on the DRC in 2003 (SC Resolution 1493) and established a targeted sanctions regime (SC Resolution 1596) currently listing dozens of individuals and entities for obstructing peace, perpetrating human rights violations, and exploiting natural resources to fund armed activity. OFAC, the EU, and the UK maintain parallel designation regimes.\n\nAs of 2026, eastern DRC is in active conflict: the M23 rebel group (widely documented as receiving Rwandan state support) controls large swaths of North and South Kivu, including major cities. This is not a frozen conflict — it is an active war zone with designated actors controlling territory and economic infrastructure.\n\nThe DRC is the world's largest producer of coltan and a major source of gold and cobalt. These conflict minerals are systematically exploited by armed groups as a primary revenue source, and payment flows from mining operations create a direct risk of inadvertently funding designated entities. KYC/KYB verification is practically impossible in conflict-affected areas. Aligned with Trails geo-block. Business prohibited." },
  { name:"Egypt", region:"Africa", fatfBlack:false, fatfGrey:false, cryptoBan:true, comp:false, bodies:[], status:P, notes:"PROHIBITED — Crypto ban.\n\nEgypt has prohibited cryptocurrency under the Central Bank Law and related regulatory instruments. The Central Bank of Egypt has issued successive circulars prohibiting financial institutions and their clients from dealing in cryptocurrencies, reinforced by religious rulings (fatwas) from Dar al-Ifta declaring crypto trading contrary to Islamic law. While enforcement has been uneven, the legal prohibition is in force and creates direct liability for BPN as a regulated financial services participant facilitating transactions involving Egyptian counterparties. Business prohibited due to crypto ban." },
  { name:"Ethiopia", region:"Africa", fatfBlack:false, fatfGrey:false, cryptoBan:false, comp:false, bodies:["OFAC","EU"], status:E, notes:"HIGH RISK — Targeted sanctions + post-conflict fragility.\n\nOFAC imposed targeted sanctions on individuals responsible for atrocities during the Tigray conflict (November 2020 – November 2022), including senior Ethiopian military officials, Eritrean Defence Forces commanders, and Amhara regional militia leaders. The EU adopted parallel measures. The Pretoria Agreement of November 2022 ended major hostilities, but sanctions posture remains in place and individual designations have not been comprehensively removed.\n\nEthiopia's financial system has weaknesses including limited AML/CFT supervision of the large informal hawala-based remittance sector and restricted correspondent banking relationships. The risk of PEP exposure — given the Ethiopian government's deep involvement in the economy — is elevated. Enhanced due diligence is required including granular beneficial ownership analysis and screening for links to sanctioned individuals or the Ethiopian military-industrial complex." },
  { name:"Haiti", region:"Americas", fatfBlack:false, fatfGrey:true, cryptoBan:false, comp:false, bodies:["OFAC","UN"], status:P, notes:"PROHIBITED — FATF grey list + OFAC/UN sanctions + collapsed state.\n\nHaiti is on the FATF grey list with deferred reporting, reflecting a complete breakdown of its AML/CFT supervisory framework rather than a temporary deficiency. The assassination of President Moïse in July 2021, the subsequent political vacuum, and the catastrophic expansion of gang control (currently controlling an estimated 80%+ of Port-au-Prince) have rendered the state non-functional.\n\nOFAC has designated gang leaders and their financial enablers under E.O. 13818 (Global Magnitsky). The UN Security Council authorised a Kenya-led Multinational Security Support Mission (SC Resolution 2699, 2023) and imposed targeted sanctions on gang leaders. There is no credible KYC/KYB infrastructure, no effective banking supervision, and no reliable civil registry. Any payment flows into Haiti carry extreme risk of benefiting gang-controlled financial intermediaries. Business prohibited." },
  { name:"Iran", region:"Middle East", fatfBlack:true, fatfGrey:false, cryptoBan:false, comp:true, bodies:["OFAC","EU","UN","UK"], status:P, notes:"PROHIBITED — FATF blacklist + comprehensive sanctions on all bodies + state sponsor of terrorism.\n\nIran is one of only two jurisdictions on the FATF blacklist (alongside North Korea), the most severe designation with a call on FATF members to apply enhanced countermeasures. Iran has been subject to comprehensive US sanctions under multiple legal authorities since 1979, including the Iranian Transactions and Sanctions Regulations (ITSR, 31 CFR Part 560), prohibiting virtually all transactions by US persons or entities. The EU, UK, and UN Security Council maintain parallel comprehensive sanctions regimes targeting Iran's nuclear programme, ballistic missile development, and support for terrorist organisations including Hezbollah, Hamas, and the Houthis.\n\nIran is the world's leading state sponsor of terrorism by US State Department assessment. The IRGC (Islamic Revolutionary Guard Corps), designated as a terrorist organisation by the US, has extensive involvement in Iran's economy. Iran also operates sophisticated cryptocurrency-based sanctions evasion operations — a key reason why the FATF blacklisting is particularly material for digital asset businesses. Business absolutely prohibited under all legal frameworks." },
  { name:"Iraq", region:"Middle East", fatfBlack:false, fatfGrey:false, cryptoBan:true, comp:false, bodies:["OFAC","EU","UK"], status:P, notes:"PROHIBITED — Crypto ban + targeted sanctions.\n\nThe Central Bank of Iraq issued a directive in 2017 prohibiting all financial institutions from transacting in cryptocurrencies, maintained and reinforced since. OFAC, the EU, and the UK maintain targeted sanctions regimes in Iraq focused on ISIS/Da'esh-affiliated entities, senior members of Iran-backed militia groups (Kata'ib Hezbollah, Asa'ib Ahl al-Haq), and individuals involved in human rights violations.\n\nIraq's financial system also faces particular risk from Iranian influence: Iran-aligned political parties control significant economic infrastructure, and there is extensive evidence of sanctions evasion using Iraq as a conduit to circumvent Iran sanctions. Business prohibited due to crypto ban and targeted sanctions exposure." },
  { name:"Kenya", region:"Africa", fatfBlack:false, fatfGrey:true, cryptoBan:false, comp:false, bodies:[], status:E, notes:"HIGH RISK — FATF grey list + inadequate VASP supervision.\n\nKenya was added to the FATF grey list with identified deficiencies including inadequate AML/CFT supervision of virtual asset service providers, weak beneficial ownership verification, limited effectiveness of financial intelligence dissemination, and insufficient confiscation of criminal proceeds.\n\nKenya is one of the highest crypto-adoption jurisdictions globally (consistently ranked top-5 in the Chainalysis Global Crypto Adoption Index), with a large unregulated VASP sector and significant crypto-to-mobile money flows (primarily via M-Pesa). The absence of effective VASP regulation creates meaningful exposure to value being moved through the Kenyan financial system without adequate AML controls.\n\nBPN onboarding in Kenya requires enhanced due diligence on counterparty VASP licensing status, mobile money provider relationships, and ultimate beneficial ownership — with particular attention to politically exposed persons given Kenya's elevated PEP risk." },
  { name:"Kuwait", region:"Middle East", fatfBlack:false, fatfGrey:true, cryptoBan:true, comp:false, bodies:[], status:P, notes:"PROHIBITED — Crypto ban + FATF grey list.\n\nThe Central Bank of Kuwait issued Circular 7/2022 imposing a comprehensive prohibition on all cryptocurrency dealings, making Kuwait one of the few Gulf states to maintain a formal crypto ban (in contrast to UAE and Bahrain, which have established regulatory frameworks). Kuwait was added to the FATF grey list at the February 2026 Plenary, reflecting identified deficiencies including inadequate supervision of the large informal value transfer sector, weak beneficial ownership transparency, and insufficient investigation of trade-based money laundering — material risks given Kuwait's position as a significant Gulf trade hub.\n\nBoth the crypto ban and the FATF grey listing independently trigger prohibition under BPN policy." },
  { name:"Lao PDR", region:"Asia", fatfBlack:false, fatfGrey:true, cryptoBan:false, comp:false, bodies:[], status:E, notes:"HIGH RISK — FATF grey list + Golden Triangle special economic zone risk.\n\nLao PDR was added to the FATF grey list in February 2025. FATF identified deficiencies including inadequate AML/CFT supervision, weak beneficial ownership frameworks, and insufficient monitoring of cross-border cash movements.\n\nThe primary risk driver is the Golden Triangle Special Economic Zone (GTSEZ) in Bokeo province, operated by the Kings Romans Group (OFAC designated). The GTSEZ is documented extensively by UN experts, law enforcement agencies, and investigative journalists as a hub for transnational organised crime — specifically drug trafficking (ya ba/methamphetamine), wildlife trafficking, human trafficking, illegal gambling, and associated money laundering. Cryptocurrency is actively used within the GTSEZ ecosystem to launder proceeds.\n\nAny BPN counterparty with connections to Bokeo, the GTSEZ, or related corporate networks should be treated as extreme risk. Enhanced due diligence required." },
  { name:"Lebanon", region:"Middle East", fatfBlack:false, fatfGrey:true, cryptoBan:false, comp:false, bodies:["OFAC","EU","UK"], status:P, notes:"PROHIBITED — FATF grey list + banking system collapse + Hezbollah financial network.\n\nLebanon was added to the FATF grey list in October 2024. The Lebanese financial system has been in collapse since 2019: sovereign debt default, Lira loss of 95%+ of its value, commercial banks imposing informal capital controls that froze depositor funds. There is no functioning correspondent banking system.\n\nOFAC, the EU, and the UK maintain extensive sanctions targeting Hezbollah, its financial network, and its political enablers — including key figures in Lebanese government, banking, and business. Hezbollah's financial infrastructure is deeply embedded in Lebanon's legitimate economy across real estate, trade finance, consumer goods, and construction, making counterparty risk assessment extremely difficult even for ostensibly legitimate businesses.\n\nThe combination of a collapsed financial system, pervasive Hezbollah financial network risk, and active OFAC/EU/UK sanctions makes business prohibited." },
  { name:"Libya", region:"Africa", fatfBlack:false, fatfGrey:false, cryptoBan:false, comp:false, bodies:["OFAC","EU","UN","UK"], status:P, notes:"PROHIBITED — UN sanctions + multi-body designations + split sovereignty.\n\nThe UN Security Council has maintained a targeted sanctions regime on Libya since 2011 (SC Resolution 1970 and successors), including an arms embargo, travel bans, and asset freezes. OFAC, the EU, and the UK each maintain parallel designation lists.\n\nLibya has had two competing governments since 2014 — the Government of National Unity (GNU) in Tripoli and the Libyan National Army (LNA/Haftar) in the east — neither of which exercises effective nationwide sovereignty. This creates an irresolvable KYC/KYB problem: a counterparty legitimate under one authority may be designated or unlawful under the other, and there is no single regulatory framework against which to assess compliance. Oil revenue diversion by both factions is extensively documented. Human trafficking and arms smuggling remain major economic activities. Business prohibited." },
  { name:"Macau", region:"Asia", fatfBlack:false, fatfGrey:false, cryptoBan:false, comp:false, bodies:[], status:E, notes:"HIGH RISK — Money laundering through gambling + capital flight vehicle.\n\nMacau is the world's largest gambling market by revenue (approximately 4–5x larger than Las Vegas), and its casino economy has been consistently identified by FATF, the US State Department, and regional financial intelligence units as a primary vehicle for large-scale money laundering and capital flight — particularly from mainland China.\n\nJunket operators — intermediaries who bring high-rolling gamblers from China — have been the subject of major prosecutorial actions (most notably the 2022 arrest of Suncity's Alvin Chau) for facilitating illicit fund movements. The use of cryptocurrency within Macau's gambling ecosystem as an alternative to casino chips is growing and largely unregulated.\n\nAny BPN corporate counterparty with a Macau presence or deriving revenue from Macau gaming operations requires enhanced due diligence including granular source of funds analysis, junket network screening, and assessment of mainland China beneficial ownership exposure." },
  { name:"Mali", region:"Africa", fatfBlack:false, fatfGrey:false, cryptoBan:false, comp:false, bodies:["EU","UN","UK"], status:P, notes:"PROHIBITED — UN/EU/UK sanctions + jihadist territorial control + military junta.\n\nMali has been subject to a UN Security Council targeted sanctions regime since 2017 (SC Resolution 2374). It was removed from the FATF grey list in June 2025 — but that delisting reflects administrative progress on technical criteria, not an improvement in the underlying risk environment. The UN arms embargo and individual designations remain in force. The EU and UK maintain targeted sanctions on junta leaders following the 2021 and 2022 military coups.\n\nMore critically, jihadist groups affiliated with al-Qaeda (JNIM) and ISIS (ISGS) control the northern two-thirds of Mali's territory following the withdrawal of French forces (Operation Barkhane) and the collapse of UN peacekeeping (MINUSMA). These groups derive financing from drug trafficking, kidnap for ransom, extortion, and illicit gold trade. Wagner Group/Africa Corps mercenaries are documented as participating in civilian massacres and resource exploitation. There is no credible KYC/KYB framework. Business prohibited." },
  { name:"Moldova", region:"Europe", fatfBlack:false, fatfGrey:false, cryptoBan:false, comp:false, bodies:[], status:E, notes:"HIGH RISK — Transnistria sanctions evasion corridor.\n\nMoldova itself is not subject to sanctions and its financial regulatory framework is improving as the country advances on its EU accession path. However, the breakaway Transnistria region (Pridnestrovian Moldavian Republic) represents a significant risk: it is not internationally recognised, is outside Moldovan government control, and is documented as a major hub for sanctions evasion, arms trafficking, and smuggling.\n\nTransnistrian entities are outside EU and OFAC sanctioned lists but fall within Russia's economic sphere. Goods, funds, and services routed through Transnistria can bypass sanctions controls on Russia. Any BPN counterparty with operations, banking relationships, or supply chains touching Transnistria must be treated as high risk. Enhanced due diligence required with geographic screening for Transnistrian exposure." },
  { name:"Monaco", region:"Europe", fatfBlack:false, fatfGrey:true, cryptoBan:false, comp:false, bodies:[], status:E, notes:"HIGH RISK — FATF grey list + UHNW money laundering risk.\n\nMonaco was added to the FATF grey list in June 2024. FATF identified deficiencies including inadequate supervision of designated non-financial businesses (lawyers, accountants, real estate agents), weak beneficial ownership verification for complex corporate structures, and insufficient investigation of high-value ML cases.\n\nMonaco's economic model is built around attracting ultra-high-net-worth individuals — including a significant number from Russia and former Soviet states — creating inherent ML risk through private banking, real estate (property values reaching hundreds of millions of euros), yacht financing, and art markets. Following Russia sanctions in 2022, Monaco was specifically identified as a location where Russian oligarchs sought to shield assets.\n\nAny BPN corporate counterparty in Monaco requires rigorous beneficial ownership analysis, source of wealth documentation, and PEP/sanctions screening — particularly for Russian-nexus individuals." },
  { name:"Morocco", region:"Africa", fatfBlack:false, fatfGrey:false, cryptoBan:true, comp:false, bodies:[], status:P, notes:"PROHIBITED — Crypto ban.\n\nBank Al-Maghrib and the Capital Market Authority jointly issued a circular in 2017 prohibiting the use of cryptocurrencies as a means of payment, holding them to be in violation of foreign exchange regulations. The prohibition is directed at all users and financial institutions. Morocco is not on the FATF grey list and does not face sanctions concerns, but the active crypto ban makes BPN engagement unlawful. Business prohibited due to crypto ban." },
  { name:"Myanmar (Burma)", region:"Asia", fatfBlack:true, fatfGrey:false, cryptoBan:false, comp:false, bodies:["OFAC","EU","UK"], status:P, notes:"PROHIBITED — FATF blacklist + comprehensive sanctions + military junta financial system control.\n\nMyanmar is on the FATF blacklist following the February 2021 military coup. The coup brought the Tatmadaw back to full power, taking control of the Myanmar Economic Corporation (MEC) and Myanmar Economic Holdings Limited (MEHL) — the two military conglomerates that dominate the formal economy. OFAC designated both MEC and MEHL as SDNs, along with Commander-in-Chief Min Aung Hlaing and senior military leaders. The EU and UK have parallel designation regimes.\n\nThe Tatmadaw has been documented using state financial infrastructure including the Central Bank of Myanmar to procure weapons and circumvent sanctions, including through cryptocurrency. The banking system is in near-collapse with most international correspondent relationships severed. Any payment flow involving Myanmar entities risks directly financing the military's ongoing atrocities against the civilian population. Business absolutely prohibited." },
  { name:"Namibia", region:"Africa", fatfBlack:false, fatfGrey:true, cryptoBan:false, comp:false, bodies:[], status:E, notes:"HIGH RISK — FATF grey list.\n\nNamibia was added to the FATF grey list following a mutual evaluation identifying deficiencies in its AML/CFT framework, including inadequate supervision of non-financial businesses and professions, limited beneficial ownership transparency, and insufficient investigation and prosecution of money laundering. Namibia is a relatively stable middle-income country with a functional government and improving regulatory posture, but the grey listing reflects strategic-level weaknesses. Enhanced due diligence required for corporate BPN onboarding." },
  { name:"Nepal", region:"Asia", fatfBlack:false, fatfGrey:true, cryptoBan:true, comp:false, bodies:[], status:P, notes:"PROHIBITED — Crypto ban + FATF grey list.\n\nNepal Rastra Bank (NRB) issued a directive in 2017 declaring all cryptocurrency-related activities — including trading, mining, investment, and transfers — to be illegal. Criminal penalties including fines, asset confiscation, and imprisonment have been imposed on individuals engaged in cryptocurrency activity. Nepal was added to the FATF grey list in February 2025, reflecting identified deficiencies in beneficial ownership frameworks, financial intelligence effectiveness, and supervision of remittance-heavy financial flows (Nepal receives remittances equivalent to approximately 25% of GDP, creating significant informal channel risk). Both grounds independently trigger prohibition under BPN policy." },
  { name:"Nicaragua", region:"Americas", fatfBlack:false, fatfGrey:false, cryptoBan:false, comp:false, bodies:["OFAC","EU","UK"], status:P, notes:"PROHIBITED — Comprehensive targeted sanctions on Ortega regime.\n\nFollowing the violent suppression of pro-democracy protests in 2018 (400+ killed), the fraudulent 2021 presidential election, and the systematic dismantling of civil society and political opposition — including the imprisonment and subsequent exile of all credible opposition candidates — the United States, European Union, and United Kingdom imposed successive rounds of targeted sanctions on President Ortega, Vice President Rosario Murillo, senior security officials, and key economic enablers.\n\nSanctioned entities include financial institutions with government links. The government exercises near-total control over the economy, meaning corporate counterparties face elevated risk of being effectively controlled by or benefiting sanctioned individuals. Business prohibited." },
  { name:"North Korea (DPRK)", region:"Asia", fatfBlack:true, fatfGrey:false, cryptoBan:true, comp:true, bodies:["OFAC","EU","UN","UK"], status:P, notes:"PROHIBITED — FATF blacklist + comprehensive sanctions across all bodies + world's most prolific state-sponsored crypto threat actor.\n\nNorth Korea is subject to the most comprehensive international sanctions of any state, including comprehensive UN Security Council sanctions (Resolutions 1718, 1874, 2087, 2094, 2270, 2321, 2356, 2371, 2375, 2397) prohibiting arms exports, oil imports beyond minimal thresholds, coal/iron/seafood exports, and financial transactions. OFAC's Korean Sanctions Regulations prohibit virtually all dealings by US persons. The EU and UK have parallel comprehensive regimes. North Korea is FATF blacklisted with a call for enhanced countermeasures.\n\nThe regime's Lazarus Group and affiliated threat actors (APT38, Kimsuky) have stolen an estimated $3–4 billion in cryptocurrency since 2017 — the single largest state-sponsored financial crime operation in history. These funds directly finance WMD and ballistic missile programmes in violation of UN Security Council resolutions. North Korea also deploys thousands of IT workers overseas using false identities to earn cryptocurrency for the regime. Any engagement with North Korean counterparties or networks is a strict liability sanctions violation that directly finances WMD proliferation. Business absolutely prohibited on all grounds." },
  { name:"North Macedonia", region:"Europe", fatfBlack:false, fatfGrey:false, cryptoBan:true, comp:false, bodies:[], status:P, notes:"PROHIBITED — Crypto ban.\n\nNorth Macedonia enacted a prohibition on the use of cryptocurrencies under its Law on Foreign Exchange Operations (2016), prohibiting residents from transacting in digital currencies. This prohibition was reinforced via regulatory guidance in 2023. Business prohibited due to crypto ban." },
  { name:"Papua New Guinea", region:"Pacific", fatfBlack:false, fatfGrey:true, cryptoBan:false, comp:false, bodies:[], status:E, notes:"HIGH RISK — FATF grey list + extractive sector opacity.\n\nPapua New Guinea was added to the FATF grey list at the February 2026 Plenary. FATF identified strategic deficiencies including inadequate beneficial ownership transparency, limited effectiveness of financial intelligence, insufficient supervision of the large resource extraction sector (gold, copper, LNG), and weak anti-corruption frameworks.\n\nPNG's extractive industries dominate the economy and are characterised by opaque ownership structures, royalty disputes, and a history of resource revenue diversion. Political corruption is systemic and the legal system has limited capacity to investigate complex financial crimes. Enhanced due diligence required, including granular beneficial ownership analysis and source of funds verification for any resource sector counterparty." },
  { name:"Qatar", region:"Middle East", fatfBlack:false, fatfGrey:false, cryptoBan:true, comp:false, bodies:[], status:P, notes:"PROHIBITED — Crypto ban.\n\nThe Qatar Financial Centre Regulatory Authority (QFCRA) and the Qatar Central Bank have imposed a comprehensive prohibition on all virtual asset and cryptocurrency activity, including trading, exchange, and any form of financial service relating to virtual currencies. Qatar is one of the most restrictive Gulf jurisdictions on cryptocurrency. Business prohibited due to crypto ban." },
  { name:"Russia", region:"Europe", fatfBlack:false, fatfGrey:false, cryptoBan:false, comp:false, bodies:["OFAC","EU","UK","UN"], status:P, notes:"PROHIBITED — Most extensive sanctions package imposed on any major economy + FATF suspension + active crypto-based evasion.\n\nFollowing Russia's full-scale invasion of Ukraine in February 2022, the US, EU, and UK imposed the largest and most complex sanctions package in financial history. This includes: OFAC SDN designations on the Central Bank of Russia, major state-owned banks (Sberbank, VTB, Gazprombank, VEB), and thousands of individuals and entities; EU sector sanctions across financial, energy, defence, and transport sectors (Regulations 269/2014, 833/2014 and 14+ successive packages); UK parallel measures; and SWIFT disconnection for most major Russian banks. FATF suspended Russia's membership in February 2024.\n\nRussia is actively exploiting cryptocurrency and third-country financial systems to fund the war effort, purchase weapons, and pay mercenaries. Any financial relationship with Russian entities — including ostensibly private companies — carries extreme risk given the state's pervasive economic ownership and active sanctions evasion operations. Business absolutely prohibited." },
  { name:"Saudi Arabia", region:"Middle East", fatfBlack:false, fatfGrey:false, cryptoBan:true, comp:false, bodies:[], status:P, notes:"PROHIBITED — Crypto ban.\n\nThe Saudi Arabian Monetary Authority (SAMA) has prohibited banks and exchange companies from dealing in Bitcoin and other cryptocurrencies. Saudi Arabia has not enacted a positive legal framework for virtual assets, and the de facto prohibition has not been lifted as of March 2026 despite widespread regional regulatory development (UAE, Bahrain). Business prohibited due to crypto ban." },
  { name:"Somalia", region:"Africa", fatfBlack:false, fatfGrey:false, cryptoBan:false, comp:false, bodies:["OFAC","EU","UN","UK"], status:P, notes:"PROHIBITED — UN arms embargo + multi-body sanctions + failed state + terrorism financing.\n\nThe UN Security Council has maintained a comprehensive arms embargo on Somalia since 1992 and a targeted sanctions regime (SC Resolution 1844 and successors) designating al-Shabaab leaders, financiers, and affiliated networks. OFAC, the EU, and the UK have parallel designation regimes.\n\nAl-Shabaab controls significant territory across southern and central Somalia, collects 'taxation' from businesses, telecommunications companies, and financial service providers operating in its areas, and has documented cryptocurrency fundraising operations. The Somali federal government controls only portions of Mogadishu and a few regional capitals. There is no functioning civil registry, no effective financial regulatory authority, and no AML/CFT supervisory framework. Any payment flow into Somalia carries an extreme risk of benefiting al-Shabaab or other designated entities through extortion or direct transfer. Business absolutely prohibited." },
  { name:"South Sudan", region:"Africa", fatfBlack:false, fatfGrey:true, cryptoBan:false, comp:false, bodies:["OFAC","EU","UN","UK"], status:P, notes:"PROHIBITED — FATF grey list + UN arms embargo + multi-body targeted sanctions + fragile state.\n\nSouth Sudan has been on the FATF grey list since its first assessment. The UN Security Council imposed an arms embargo in 2018 (SC Resolution 2428) and a targeted sanctions regime designating individuals responsible for actions threatening peace, security, and stability. OFAC, the EU, and the UK maintain parallel designation regimes.\n\nSouth Sudan is consistently ranked among the world's most fragile states: it has experienced recurrent civil war since independence in 2011, with widespread atrocities documented by the UN Commission on Human Rights. Oil revenues — the country's only significant export — are extensively diverted by political and military elites through shell companies and international banking relationships. There is no credible AML/CFT framework, no functional banking supervision, and no beneficial ownership infrastructure. Business prohibited." },
  { name:"Sri Lanka", region:"Asia", fatfBlack:false, fatfGrey:false, cryptoBan:false, comp:false, bodies:[], status:E, notes:"HIGH RISK — Post-crisis financial system fragility.\n\nSri Lanka experienced a catastrophic economic crisis in 2022, culminating in the country's first-ever sovereign default, the president's flight from the country, and an IMF emergency bailout programme. The crisis was characterised by near-total foreign reserve depletion, hyperinflationary pressure, fuel and medicine shortages, and a collapse in formal banking sector capacity.\n\nThe aftermath has left the financial system materially weakened: multiple banks required recapitalisation, AML/CFT supervision resources were diverted to crisis management, and the informal hawala sector expanded significantly as the formal system struggled. While the IMF programme has stabilised the macroeconomic situation, the supervisory infrastructure remains fragile. Enhanced due diligence required for BPN corporate onboarding, including source of funds verification and assessment of banking counterparty soundness." },
  { name:"Sudan", region:"Africa", fatfBlack:false, fatfGrey:false, cryptoBan:false, comp:false, bodies:["OFAC","EU","UK","UN"], status:P, notes:"PROHIBITED — Active civil war + comprehensive multi-body sanctions + banking system collapse.\n\nSudan has been in a devastating civil war since April 2023, when fighting broke out between the Sudanese Armed Forces (SAF) and the Rapid Support Forces (RSF) paramilitary. The conflict has produced one of the world's largest humanitarian crises with millions displaced and widespread atrocity crimes documented by the UN. OFAC, the EU, and the UK maintain targeted sanctions on senior officials of both the SAF and RSF, including RSF commander Mohamed Hamdan Dagalo (Hemeti).\n\nSudan's banking system has effectively collapsed: Khartoum's banking district was a major conflict zone, financial infrastructure has been destroyed or displaced, and international correspondent relationships have been severed. There is no functioning AML/CFT supervisory authority. Business absolutely prohibited." },
  { name:"Syria", region:"Middle East", fatfBlack:false, fatfGrey:true, cryptoBan:false, comp:false, bodies:["EU","UK"], status:P, notes:"PROHIBITED — Residual EU/UK sanctions + FATF grey list + post-conflict AML/CFT impossibility.\n\nOFAC's comprehensive Syria sanctions were lifted effective July 1 2025 (Executive Order 14312) and the Caesar Syria Civilian Protection Act was repealed in December 2025. The EU lifted all sectoral economic sanctions on May 29 2025. OFAC is therefore no longer a legal basis for blocking Syria.\n\nResidual legal exposure: The EU retained targeted asset freezes on Assad-linked individuals and entities through at least June 1 2026. Both the EU and UK arms embargoes and human rights designations remain in force and are the current legal basis for prohibition.\n\nFATF grey list: Syria remains grey listed with no exit date confirmed.\n\nAML/CFT impossibility: Syria has no functioning financial regulatory infrastructure. Fourteen years of civil war destroyed or displaced all supervisory institutions — no effective central bank supervisory capacity, no beneficial ownership registry, no AML/CFT compliance sector, and no credible counterparty verification process. Multiple armed factions continue to control different regions.\n\nBusiness prohibited pending development of viable supervisory infrastructure, full FATF exit, and expiry of EU/UK residual designations." },
  { name:"Tunisia", region:"Africa", fatfBlack:false, fatfGrey:false, cryptoBan:true, comp:false, bodies:[], status:P, notes:"PROHIBITED — Crypto ban.\n\nThe Central Bank of Tunisia issued a directive in 2018 prohibiting all transactions in cryptocurrencies, including payments, exchange, mining, and advertising. Criminal penalties including imprisonment have been imposed on individuals engaged in cryptocurrency activity in Tunisia. Tunisia is not on the FATF grey list and is not subject to significant sanctions concerns, but the active crypto ban — with criminal enforcement — makes BPN engagement unlawful. Business prohibited due to crypto ban." },
  { name:"Ukraine", region:"Europe", fatfBlack:false, fatfGrey:false, cryptoBan:false, comp:false, bodies:[], status:E, notes:"HIGH RISK — Active war + wartime AML/CFT risk.\n\nUkraine itself is not subject to sanctions and is not on the FATF grey list. However, the ongoing Russian invasion — now in its fourth year — creates elevated AML/CFT risks. Specifically: (1) corruption and diversion risk is elevated in wartime environments, with significant international aid flows creating misappropriation opportunities; (2) the proximity of active frontlines means counterparties may have de facto operations in or near Russian-controlled territory; (3) there is documented use of cryptocurrency for both legitimate humanitarian funding and sanctions evasion by Russia-adjacent networks operating through Ukrainian-based intermediaries.\n\nNote: Russian-occupied regions (Crimea, Donetsk, Luhansk, Kherson, Zaporizhzhia) are listed separately as Prohibited due to comprehensive sanctions. EDD required for all Ukrainian corporate onboarding." },
  { name:"Ukraine (Crimea)", region:"Europe", fatfBlack:false, fatfGrey:false, cryptoBan:false, comp:true, bodies:["OFAC","EU","UK"], status:P, notes:"PROHIBITED — Comprehensive OFAC/EU/UK territory-wide sanctions.\n\nOFAC E.O. 13685 imposes a comprehensive geographic prohibition on all transactions involving the Crimea region — not a listed-party requirement but a sector-wide prohibition covering all transactions, services, imports, and exports regardless of counterparty identity. The EU and UK have parallel comprehensive prohibitions. Business absolutely prohibited." },
  { name:"Ukraine (Donetsk)", region:"Europe", fatfBlack:false, fatfGrey:false, cryptoBan:false, comp:true, bodies:["OFAC","EU","UK"], status:P, notes:"PROHIBITED — Comprehensive OFAC/EU/UK territory-wide sanctions.\n\nOFAC extended its Ukrainian territory sanctions framework to the so-called Donetsk People's Republic following Russia's 2022 annexation. These are comprehensive geographic prohibitions covering all transactions, services, imports, and exports involving this territory regardless of counterparty identity. The EU and UK have parallel comprehensive prohibitions. Business absolutely prohibited." },
  { name:"Ukraine (Luhansk)", region:"Europe", fatfBlack:false, fatfGrey:false, cryptoBan:false, comp:true, bodies:["OFAC","EU","UK"], status:P, notes:"PROHIBITED — Comprehensive OFAC/EU/UK territory-wide sanctions.\n\nOFAC extended its Ukrainian territory sanctions framework to the so-called Luhansk People's Republic following Russia's 2022 annexation. These are comprehensive geographic prohibitions covering all transactions, services, imports, and exports involving this territory regardless of counterparty identity. The EU and UK have parallel comprehensive prohibitions. Business absolutely prohibited." },
  { name:"Ukraine (Kherson)", region:"Europe", fatfBlack:false, fatfGrey:false, cryptoBan:false, comp:true, bodies:["OFAC","EU","UK","Canada"], status:P, notes:"PROHIBITED — Comprehensive sanctions including Canadian law.\n\nRussia annexed Kherson Oblast in September 2022. OFAC extended its Ukrainian territory sanctions framework to cover Kherson. The EU and UK imposed parallel comprehensive prohibitions.\n\nCritically, Canada enacted the Special Economic Measures (Ukraine) Regulations SOR/2022-203, effective September 29 2022, imposing a comprehensive dealings prohibition on Kherson Oblast — covering investments, exports, imports, financial services, technical assistance, and tourism services. As Trails is offered via a Canadian-incorporated entity, the Canadian dealings ban creates direct statutory liability in addition to OFAC/EU/UK exposure. Business absolutely prohibited." },
  { name:"Ukraine (Zaporizhzhia)", region:"Europe", fatfBlack:false, fatfGrey:false, cryptoBan:false, comp:true, bodies:["OFAC","EU","UK","Canada"], status:P, notes:"PROHIBITED — Comprehensive sanctions including Canadian law.\n\nRussia annexed Zaporizhzhia Oblast in September 2022. OFAC extended its Ukrainian territory sanctions framework to cover Zaporizhzhia. The EU and UK imposed parallel comprehensive prohibitions.\n\nCanada enacted the Special Economic Measures (Ukraine) Regulations SOR/2022-203, effective September 29 2022, imposing a comprehensive dealings prohibition on Zaporizhzhia Oblast — covering investments, exports, imports, financial services, technical assistance, and tourism services. As Trails is offered via a Canadian-incorporated entity, the Canadian dealings ban creates direct statutory liability in addition to OFAC/EU/UK exposure. Business absolutely prohibited." },
  { name:"Venezuela", region:"Americas", fatfBlack:false, fatfGrey:true, cryptoBan:false, comp:false, bodies:["OFAC","EU","UK","Canada"], status:P, notes:"PROHIBITED — FATF grey list + OFAC/EU/UK/Canada sanctions + PDVSA sanctions evasion operations.\n\nVenezuela was added to the FATF grey list in June 2024. OFAC has imposed successive rounds of targeted sanctions on the Maduro regime since 2015, including designations of President Maduro himself, senior government and military officials, PDVSA, and the Maduro-aligned cryptocurrency Petro. The EU extended its Venezuela sanctions in December 2025 through to January 2027 (69 individuals designated). The UK and Canada have parallel targeted sanctions — Canada sanctioned 14 additional Venezuelan officials in January 2025 and a further 8 in March 2025, bringing its total to 139 designated individuals.\n\nVenezuela presents an extreme sanctions evasion risk: PDVSA and regime-connected entities have been extensively documented using cryptocurrency, gold smuggling, and correspondent banking relationships in third countries (Turkey, Russia, Iran) to circumvent US and EU sanctions. The Alex Saab prosecution revealed the scale of international financial networks used to access the global financial system in violation of sanctions. Any Venezuelan corporate counterparty presents elevated risk of being controlled by or benefiting sanctioned parties. Business prohibited." },
  { name:"Vietnam", region:"Asia", fatfBlack:false, fatfGrey:true, cryptoBan:false, comp:false, bodies:[], status:E, notes:"HIGH RISK — FATF grey list + inadequate VASP supervision in high-adoption jurisdiction.\n\nVietnam is on the FATF grey list with identified deficiencies including inadequate AML/CFT supervision of virtual asset service providers, weak beneficial ownership transparency, limited effectiveness of financial intelligence, and insufficient investigation of trade-based money laundering.\n\nVietnam ranks among the top five globally in cryptocurrency adoption (Chainalysis Global Crypto Adoption Index), with a large retail crypto trading population, significant DeFi and NFT activity, and a growing number of unregulated VASPs. The combination of high adoption and inadequate supervision creates meaningful AML/CFT exposure. Enhanced due diligence required including VASP licensing verification and counterparty AML programme assessment." },
  { name:"Virgin Islands (UK)", region:"Caribbean", fatfBlack:false, fatfGrey:true, cryptoBan:false, comp:false, bodies:[], status:E, notes:"HIGH RISK — FATF grey list + offshore financial centre opacity.\n\nThe British Virgin Islands was added to the FATF grey list in June 2025. FATF identified deficiencies including inadequate beneficial ownership verification and registration for BVI companies and trusts, weak supervision of company service providers, and insufficient investigation and prosecution of money laundering — particularly significant given the BVI's role as one of the world's largest offshore corporate registration centres.\n\nBVI entities are extensively used in complex beneficial ownership structures globally. The FATF grey listing reflects that BVI's beneficial ownership registry lacks the real-time verification and law enforcement access required by FATF standards. Any BPN corporate counterparty incorporated or holding assets through BVI structures requires enhanced beneficial ownership diligence." },
  { name:"Yemen", region:"Middle East", fatfBlack:false, fatfGrey:true, cryptoBan:false, comp:false, bodies:["OFAC","EU","UN","UK"], status:P, notes:"PROHIBITED — FATF grey list + UN arms embargo (renewed to Nov 2026) + Houthi SDGT designation + failed state.\n\nYemen has been in civil war since 2014. The UN Security Council renewed the Yemen sanctions regime (SC Resolution 2801, November 2025) until 14 November 2026 — covering asset freezes, travel bans, and a targeted arms embargo. OFAC designated the Houthis (Ansar Allah) as a Specially Designated Global Terrorist (SDGT) in 2024, with additional Houthi-linked individuals and entities designated in July 2025. The EU and UK maintain parallel designation regimes.\n\nThere is no functioning unified financial system: the Central Bank has de facto split into two institutions (Aden and Sanaa) with incompatible monetary policies and no effective supervisory capacity. Houthi-controlled areas use an entirely informal financial system. The combination of active multi-body sanctions, the Houthi SDGT designation, and completely non-functional AML/CFT infrastructure makes engagement impossible. Business prohibited." },
  { name:"Zimbabwe", region:"Africa", fatfBlack:false, fatfGrey:false, cryptoBan:false, comp:false, bodies:["EU"], status:P, notes:"PROHIBITED — EU arms embargo + residual OFAC Global Magnitsky designations + governance risk.\n\nThe Zimbabwe sanctions landscape has changed materially. OFAC revoked its Zimbabwe-specific sanctions regime in March 2024, though certain Zimbabwean individuals remain designated under the Global Magnitsky programme. The UK removed the last entries from its Zimbabwe sanctions list in May 2025. The EU delisted its last remaining entity (Zimbabwe Defence Industries) in February 2025 and as of February 2026 (Council Decision 2026/383) the EU Zimbabwe regime is limited to an arms embargo only, renewed to February 2027 — there are no longer any EU targeted financial sanctions on individuals.\n\nNotwithstanding the significant sanctions relief, Zimbabwe remains prohibited for BPN on governance and residual designation grounds: ZANU-PF's pervasive influence over the formal economy creates PEP risk that is difficult to screen without designated party hooks, and the residual OFAC Global Magnitsky designations on certain individuals remain active. The arms embargo also limits certain categories of financial service.\n\nNote: This entry should be reviewed for potential downgrade to EDD at next compliance review cycle given the scale of sanctions relief." },
  ...ALLOWED_COUNTRIES,
];

